<main id="main-content" style="background: var(--bg-page);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="about-body">

      <!-- What ACW does -->
      <section class="about-section" aria-labelledby="what-heading">
        <h2 id="what-heading">What we track</h2>
        <p>
          ACW is a living registry of open-source AT projects. Every project gets a
          <strong>health score</strong> (0–10) computed from five dimensions:
          Activity (25%), Replicability (30%), Community (15%), AT-Specific signals (20%),
          and Provenance (10%). Scores are refreshed by automated GitHub data fetches.
        </p>
        <p>
          Projects are classified with <strong>ISO 9999 codes</strong> — the international
          standard for assistive products — so ACW's data can connect to clinical
          databases and procurement systems that use the same taxonomy.
        </p>
        <ul class="differentiator-list" aria-label="What makes ACW different">
          <li>Live health monitoring — not a static list frozen in time</li>
          <li>Machine-readable schema (YAML + JSON) designed for downstream tooling</li>
          <li>ISO 9999 codes linking to clinical and procurement taxonomies</li>
          <li>AT-specific signals: co-design, end-user docs, known deployments</li>
          <li>Open data (CC0) — download, fork, remix without restriction</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- How ACW fits the ecosystem -->
      <section class="about-section" aria-labelledby="ecosystem-heading">
        <h2 id="ecosystem-heading">How ACW fits the ecosystem</h2>
        <p>
          ACW is not the first AT registry, and it is not trying to replace any of them.
          The open AT ecosystem is better served by a network of complementary resources
          than by competing for the same audience. Where the same project appears in
          another registry, ACW links out.
        </p>

        <table class="registry-table" aria-label="Comparison of AT registries">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Registry</th>
              <th>Focus</th>
              <th>What it does well</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="acw-row">
              <td>Assistive Commons Watch</td>
              <td>Open-source AT projects</td>
              <td>Live health scores, ISO 9999 codes, machine-readable schema, AT-specific signals</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><a href="https://www.makersmakingchange.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Makers Making Change</a></td>
              <td>DIY &amp; maker AT hardware</td>
              <td>200+ devices, build files, community support, instructional videos</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><a href="https://openassistive.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">openassistive.org</a></td>
              <td>Open-source AT software &amp; hardware</td>
              <td>Curated catalogue with plain-language descriptions for end users</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><a href="https://github.com/openassistive/awesome-assistivetech" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">awesome-assistivetech</a></td>
              <td>Curated link list</td>
              <td>Fast overview of the landscape, easy to contribute via GitHub PR</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><a href="https://www.openassistivetech.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GOAT</a></td>
              <td>Global open AT catalogue</td>
              <td>Community-built product pages, broad hardware and software coverage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><a href="https://www.eastin.eu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">EASTIN</a></td>
              <td>European AT product database</td>
              <td>ISO 9999 taxonomy, links to national databases across 10+ countries</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Contributing -->
      <section class="about-section" aria-labelledby="contribute-heading">
        <h2 id="contribute-heading">Contributing</h2>
        <p>
          ACW is open source. You can submit new projects, correct metadata, or improve
          the health-scoring model via GitHub.
        </p>
        <p>
          Project data lives in <code style="font-size: 13px; background: var(--bg-page); padding: 1px 5px; border-radius: 4px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">_data/projects/*.yaml</code> —
          one file per project, validated against a Pydantic schema. The full schema and
          a guide to contributing are in the repository.
        </p>
        <div style="margin-top: 16px; display: flex; gap: 10px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
